# Day 20 - Subarrays with K Different Integers

## Problem Statement
Given an integer array `nums` and an integer `k`, return the number of good subarrays of `nums`.

A good subarray is one that contains exactly `k` distinct integers.

A subarray is a contiguous part of an array.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    int atmost(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int left = 0;
        int missing = k;
        int count = 0;
        unordered_map<int, int> freq;

        for (int right = 0; right < nums.size(); right++) {
            if (freq[nums[right]] == 0) {
                missing--;
            }

            freq[nums[right]]++;

            while (missing < 0) {
                freq[nums[left]]--;

                if (freq[nums[left]] == 0) {
                    missing++;
                }

                left++;
            }

            count += right - left + 1;
        }

        return count;
    }

    int subarraysWithKDistinct(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        return atmost(nums, k) - atmost(nums, k - 1);
    }
};



## Time Complexity
**O(n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(k)**

## Approach
This solution uses the **Sliding Window** technique together with the **At Most** approach. Instead of directly counting subarrays with exactly `k` distinct integers, it first counts the number of subarrays containing **at most `k`** distinct integers and **at most `k - 1`** distinct integers. The difference between these two counts gives the number of subarrays with exactly `k` distinct integers. An `unordered_map` is used to maintain the frequency of elements inside the current window, while the `missing` variable tracks how many additional distinct elements can still be included. Whenever the number of distinct elements exceeds the limit, the window is shrunk from the left until it becomes valid again. For every valid window, all subarrays ending at the current index are counted, resulting in an overall linear-time solution.
